Application Exercise 2: Exploratory data analysis

Willem van den Boom

To practise exploratory data analysis, let us have a look at the data set built into R named CO2. One can load it into R as follows:

data(CO2)

Let us read what these data are about. Since this is a builtin dataset, it comes with R documentation.

?CO2

summary provides an overview of the data contents.

summary(CO2)
##      Plant             Type         Treatment       conc     
##  Qn1    : 7   Quebec     :42   nonchilled:42   Min.   :  95  
##  Qn2    : 7   Mississippi:42   chilled   :42   1st Qu.: 175  
##  Qn3    : 7                                    Median : 350  
##  Qc1    : 7                                    Mean   : 435  
##  Qc3    : 7                                    3rd Qu.: 675  
##  Qc2    : 7                                    Max.   :1000  
##  (Other):42                                                  
##      uptake     
##  Min.   : 7.70  
##  1st Qu.:17.90  
##  Median :28.30  
##  Mean   :27.21  
##  3rd Qu.:37.12  
##  Max.   :45.50  
##

Let us create exploratory plots to investigate the following questions:

  1. Is the distribution of uptake unimodal?
hist(CO2$uptake)

The histogram shows 2 modes, so the distribution is not unimodal.

  1. Does uptake differ by Treatment?
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(CO2, aes(x=uptake, fill=Treatment)) + geom_density(alpha = .3, color = NA)

Yes, those which are chilled often have a lower uptake that those which are not chilled.

  1. Is there a trend between uptake and conc?
plot(uptake ~ conc, data=CO2)

boxplot(uptake ~ conc, data=CO2)

Yes, a higher ambient concentration of carbon dioxide corresponds with a higher uptake of carbon dioxide. However, the trend shows diminishing returns for increase concentration.
